s://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/main/en/main_classes/text_generation)\n","output_type":"stream"},{"name":"stdout","text":"promptThe AI agent quickly analyzed the data stream, and its core decision was to\nGenerated Output The AI agent quickly analyzed the data stream, and its core decision was to use a new algorithm to make it more efficient.\n\n\n\n\nThe goal was to use the algorithm to produce the most accurate information about a user's personal computer.\n\nIn the end, the AI agent was able to determine that the user's personal computer was more efficient than the computer it was working on.\nThe first step was to determine the user's computer's speed and accuracy.\nThe algorithm was able to determine that the user's computer was more efficient than the computer it was working on.\nOnce the algorithm was finished, it was ready to take a look at the user's computer and analyze the data stream.\nIn this video, we show how the algorithm can reduce the cost of the AI agent.\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":20},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Tokenization","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# clean\n# split\n# map\n# output -> is the unique integer ids\n\nimport re\n\ntext = \"This is an expample for traditional tokenization\"\n\nclean_text = re.sub(r'[^\\w\\s]','', text).lower()\n\ntokens = clean_text.split()\n\nvocab = {word: i for i, word in enumerate(set(tokens),1)}\n\ntoken_id = [vocab[token] for token in tokens]\n\nprint(f\"Tokens: {tokens}\")\nprint(f\"TokenId: {token_id}\")\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.718321Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.718743Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.718584Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.718607Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 4 Ways of Tokenizations\n- Sentence Tokenization -> [\"Hello!\", \"how are you doing?\"]\n- word Tokenization -> [\"Hello!\", \"how\", \"are\", \"you\", \"doing?\"]\n- sub - word Tokenization -> [\"He\",\"llo\",\"!\"]\n- N- gram Tokenization -> \"Grouping adjcent words into chunks of N size: 'I like AI'->[\"i like\", \"like AI\"]","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#   Tools for Tokenization: Nltp, Spacy , HuggingFace transformer","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import nltk\nfrom nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize, sent_tokenize\n\ntext  = \"We can use Natural Language toolkit to tokenize the text. it will tokenize the text we pass.\"\n\n# word tokenization\nwords = word_tokenize(text)\n\n# sentence tokenization\nsentence = sent_tokenize(text)\n\nprint(f\"word Tokenization: {words}\")\nprint(f\"sentence Tokenization : {sentence}\")\n\n\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.721176Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.721674Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.721435Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.721468Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Spacy \nIts a object oriented approach, \nit does not return list of strings -> it returns Doc object (like a container) that contains Token object with extra informations [Stop words etc]\n- spaCy is \"smarter.\" When you process text, it returns a Doc object, which is like a smart container. Inside this container are Token objects.\n- Think of a **Token** object as a \"folder\" for each word that contains a bunch of hidden \"sticky notes\" (attributes) describing that word.\n##### Breaking it down:\n- The Doc Object: This represents the entire original sentence. It \"owns\" the tokens and remembers their order.\n\n- The Token Object: Instead of just being the letters \"running\", it’s an object that knows its own \"identity.\"\n### The \"Extra Information\" (Attributes)\nEvery token has built-in variables (attributes) you can check.   \n#### Here are the ones you mentioned:\n**token.is_stop:** A True/False value. It checks if the word is a \"Stop Word\" (common words like \"the\", \"is\", \"at\" that usually don't carry much meaning).  \n**token.pos_:** The Part of Speech. It tells you if the word is a NOUN, VERB, or ADJ.  \n**token.lemma_:** The \"base form\" of the word. (e.g., \"running\" becomes \"run\"). \n**token.is_punct:** A True/False value. Tells you if the token is just a comma or period.  \n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:d09ba2b1-dd97-48a8-ab57-3bcdaaa69588.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"d09ba2b1-dd97-48a8-ab57-3bcdaaa69588.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Spacy \n\nimport spacy\n\nnlp = spacy.load(\"en_core_web_sm\") # lang model \n\ntext = \"tihs is an example of the spacy tool\"\n\ndoc = nlp(text)\n\ntokens = [(token.text, token.pos_, token.is_stop) for token in doc]\n\nprint(f\"Spacy tokenization: {tokens}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.723202Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.723660Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.723405Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.723427Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from transformers import AutoTokenizer\n\n# Gpt2 and BERT\n\ntokenize_gpt = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('gpt2')\nprint(tokenize_gpt.tokenize(\"this is gpt styled tokenization.\"))\n\ntokenize_bert = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\nprint(tokenize_bert.tokenize(\"this is BERT styled tokenization.\"))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.726922Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.727340Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.727119Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.727188Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# GEN AI Chapter 2\n\n**Tokenization**: the process of slicing of sentence into a sequcne of \"word\", \"subword\" with mapping it with unique integer ID's which reperents the input text.  \n**Tranformer**: ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Generating Stentence Embeddings with sentence tranformers","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Sentence Transformers library is built on pytorch and Huggingface Transformers -> to generated high quanlity dense sentence and paragraph embeddings.  \n\n#### Algorithm:  \n**Model Selection**:Choose an embedding model, which is optimized for sentence-level tasks.  \n**Tokenization**: The model internally tokenizes the input sentences.  \n**Transformer Pass**: the tokens pass through the transformer model.  \n**Pooling**: Since the transformer outputs an embedding vector for each token we need ne vector for entire sentence.  \nPooling aggregates all token vectors into a single, fixed-size sentence vector.  \n**Normalization**: the final vector is usually normalized(len=1) so vector similarity (cosine similarity) only depends on the angle between the vectors, not thier magnitude.\n\n\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Sentence Transformers (SBERT) are specialized Python models—built on architectures like BERT, RoBERTa, and MiniLM—that generate dense, fixed-size vector representations (embeddings) of text. By using Hugging Face (https://huggingface.co/blog/how-to-train-sentence-transformers) transformers paired with pooling layers, they map input sentences to semantic space, enabling fast similarity search, clustering, and semantic retrieval. [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]  \nKey Characteristics & Top Models \n\n• Bi-Encoder Architecture: Efficiently calculates embeddings for text or images, crucial for large-scale retrieval. \n• Performance: Superior to traditional bag-of-words by capturing context, syntax, and word order. \n• Popular Pretrained Models: \n\n\t• all-MiniLM-L6-v2: Fast, versatile, and highly popular for general-purpose semantic search. \n\t• all-mpnet-base-v2: Offers the best quality for many semantic search tasks. \n\t• Multilingual E5 (e.g., intfloat/multilingual-e5-large): Excellent for cross-lingual tasks and Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG). \n\t• Instructor (e.g., hkunlp/instructor-large): Allows task-specific instructions to be added for improved embedding quality. [1, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10]  \n\nModel Components \nSentence Transformer models generally consist of a sequential pipeline: \n\n1. Transformer: Processes input tokens and produces contextualized word embeddings. \n2. Pooling: Aggregates word embeddings into a single fixed-length vector (e.g., Mean Pooling). \n3. Dense & Normalization (Optional): Refines embeddings, often normalizing them for cosine similarity calculations. [3, 11]  \n\nTypical Applications \n\n• Semantic Search: Matching queries with relevant documents by calculating cosine similarity, often used in RAG systems. \n• Sentence Similarity: Identifying how closely related two texts are. \n• Clustering: Grouping similar documents or sentences. \n• Cross-Lingual Search: Finding documents across different languages (e.g., using ). \n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Import necessary libaries\nfrom sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer\nimport numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.729285Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.730019Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.729778Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.729813Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Model Selection\nmodel = SentenceTransformer('all-MiniLM-L6-v2')\nprint(\"Model Loaded\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.731037Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.732084Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.731889Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.731916Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Defining our Input Sentence\nsentences = [\"A dog is chassing a bright red ball on a sunny green filed.\",\n             \"The dog seem to be enjoying the bright sunny day at park.\",\n            \"The canine pursues a crimson sphere across the lawn.\",\n            \"I'm Planning to bake an apple pie for the picnic next weekend.\",\n            \"A new laptop was purchased from the tech store today.\"]","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.733216Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.733562Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.733417Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.733438Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Generate embeddings\nprint(\"\\nGenerating embeddings for the sentences...\")\nembeddings = model.encode(sentences)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.735461Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.735789Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.735642Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.735661Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(f\"Shape of the embeddings: {embeddings.shape}\")# dense numerical vector representation/embedding\nprint(f\"Embedding dimension (d_k): {embeddings.shape[1]}\") #dimension mathematically encodes semantic meaning or its corresponding sentence, allowing model to determine the relationships between text by menaing the distance or angle b/w these vectors in  the 384D space.\nprint(f\"Sample of the first embedding vector: {embeddings[0][:5]}....\") #values that represents the sentence's meaning.\n\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.737200Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.737541Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.737396Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.737417Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Calculating sematic meaning (cosine similarity)\n\n# cosine similarity matrix for all pairs\nsimilarity_matrix = cosine_similarity(embeddings)\n\n\n# Extract and dispaly the key similarities\n# difference in the each sentences with each other\ns1_s2_sim = similarity_matrix[0,1]\ns1_s3_sim = similarity_matrix[0,2]\ns1_s4_sim = similarity_matrix[0,3]\ns1_s5_sim = similarity_matrix[0,4]\n\n\n# if cosine score is 1.0 identicall 0.0 = unrelated\nprint(f\"Similarity (s1 vs s2): {s1_s2_sim}\")\nprint(f\"Similarity (s1 vs s3): {s1_s3_sim}\")\nprint(f\"Similarity (s1 vs s4): {s1_s4_sim}\")\n\n\n\n\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.741307Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.742080Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.741817Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.741845Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"for i in range(len(sentences)):\n    for j in range(i+1, len(sentences)):\n        score = similarity_matrix[i,j]\n        \n        print(f\"Comparing Sentence {i+1} and {j+1}:\")\n        print(f\"Score: {score:.4f}\")\n\n        if score > 0.99:\n            print(\"Bound to Similary meaning\")\n        else:\n            print(\"Not Bounded by similar meaning\")\n        ","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.743919Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.744396Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.744145Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.744215Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# RAG SYSTEM","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"!pip install faiss-cpu","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.746325Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.746880Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.746583Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:38:26.746620Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Building a rah system using all that we have learned so far\n\n# laoding the needed libraries\n\nimport pypdf #---> to read the pdf\nimport numpy as np\nfrom transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSeq2SeqLM #--> tokenize the pdf content by sequences\nfrom sentence_transformers  import SentenceTransformer #---> for embeddings\nimport faiss #--> to store the embedded vectors\n\n\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:39:09.008600Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-25T11:39:09.008943Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:39:09.015346Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:39:09.008914Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:39:09.013941Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":21},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Load the pdf\ndef load_and_chunk_pdf(file_path, chunk_size=512, overlap=50):\n    \"\"\"Loads a PDF, extract text and splits it into chunks\"\"\"\n    print(\"Loading and chunking PDF....\")\n    reader = pypdf.PdfReader(file_path)\n    text = \"\"\n    for page in reader.pages:\n        text += page.extract_text() or \"\"\n\n\n    chunks = []\n    for i in range(0, len(text), chunk_size - overlap):\n        chunks.append(text[i:i + chunk_size])\n    print(f\"created {len(chunks)} chunks.\")\n    return chunks\n\npdf_chunks = load_and_chunk_pdf('/kaggle/input/datasets/dhanyathas/visionaid-textbook-pdf/VisionAid_Textbook.pdf')","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-25T11:48:18.804762Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-25T11:48:18.805903Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-25T11:48:21.183295Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-25T11:48:18.805858Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-25T11:48:21.182120Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Loading and chunking PDF....\ncreated 100 chunks.\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":30},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Embedding model\nembedding_model = SentenceTransformer('all-MiniLM-L6-v2')","metad